{"senses": [{"examples": [{"text": "amīcum parāre", "bold_text_offsets": [[0, 6]], "translation": "to make a friend; to befriend", "english": "to make a friend; to befriend", "bold_translation_offsets": [[10, 16], [23, 29]], "type": "example"}, {"text": "[Agorastocles] Ita me di ament, tardo amico nihil est quicquam inaequius,\npraesertim homini amanti, qui quidquid agit properat omnia.\nSicut ego hos duco advocatos, homines spissigradissimos,", "ref": "c. 194 BCE, Plautus, Poenulus 3.1.1–4", "english": "[Agorastocles] May gods so love me, nothing is more unfair than having a slothful friend, even more so for a man in love, who in doing anything must all expedite. So I lead them, having called them forth, the most slow-paced men of them all, slower than freight ships [corbitae] upon a quiet sea.", "translation": "[Agorastocles] May gods so love me, nothing is more unfair than having a slothful friend, even more so for a man in love, who in doing anything must all expedite. So I lead them, having called them forth, the most slow-paced men of them all, slower than freight ships [corbitae] upon a quiet sea.", "type": "quotation", "roman": "tardiores quam corbitae sunt in tranquillo mari."}], "links": [["male", "male"], ["friend", "friend"]], "synonyms": [{"word": "necessārius"}, {"word": "comes"}, {"word": "sodālis"}, {"word": "concordia"}], "categories": ["Latin terms with quotations", "Latin terms with usage examples"], "glosses": ["male friend"], "tags": ["declension-2"]}, {"links": [["Augustan", "Augustan"], ["courtier", "courtier"], ["minister", "minister"], ["counsellor", "counsellor"]], "raw_glosses": ["(Augustan and later) courtier, minister, counsellor"], "qualifier": "Augustan and later", "glosses": ["courtier, minister, counsellor"], "tags": ["declension-2"]}], "pos": "noun", "head_templates": [{"name": "la-noun", "args": {"1": "amīcus<2>", "f": "amīca"}, "expansion": "amīcus m (genitive amīcī, feminine amīca); second declension"}], "categories": ["Latin 3-s